# Viral Vector Injection Parameters in Neuroscience Research: A Comprehensive Review

**Date:** March 2026\
**Prepared for:** Neuroscience Research Community\
**Scope:** Injection parameters for optogenetics, chemogenetics, and
viral tracing in rodent and non-human primate (NHP) models

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Executive Summary

This report synthesizes injection parameters from 30+ peer-reviewed
studies using viral vectors for circuit manipulation and tracing in
neuroscience research. The focus is on practical parameters including
viral serotypes, titers, injection volumes, flow rates, stereotaxic
coordinates, and expression times.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1. VIRAL VECTOR SYSTEMS

### 1.1 Adeno-Associated Virus (AAV) - Most Common Platform

| Study | Serotype | Promoter | Titer | Application |
|--------------|--------------|--------------|--------------|----------------|
| **Hirabayashi et al., 2024** | AAV2 | CMV | 2.2-2.3 × 10¹³ GC/ml | Chemogenetics (DREADD) in OFC |
| **Sano et al., 2020** | AAV2, AAV-DJ | CAG | 1.0-1.5 × 10¹³ vg/ml | Retrograde labeling via AAVR |
| **Watakabe et al., 2015** | AAV1, AAV5, AAV7, AAV8, AAV9 | CaMKIIα, SynI | 0.4-2.5 × 10¹³ GC/ml | Comparative transduction in marmoset/macaque |
| **Noritake et al., 2023** | AAV-DJ, AAV2-retro | CAGGS, EF1α | 7.5-9.8 × 10¹² vg/ml | Chemogenetic circuit dissection |
| **Watanabe et al., 2020** | AAV2, AAV5 | CAG | 1.5-4.3 × 10¹² GC/ml | Optogenetic stimulation of motor cortex |
| **Trautmann et al., 2021** | AAV1 | CaMKIIα, hSyn | Not specified | GCaMP6f imaging in motor cortex |
| **Miura et al., 2020** | AAV5 | CaMKII | 1.0 × 10¹⁴ GC/ml | Insular cortex GCaMP6f imaging |
| **Gerits et al., 2015** | AAV2/1, AAV2/5, AAV2/7, AAV2/8 | CaMKIIα | Not specified | Serotype comparison in macaque |

**Key Findings:** - **AAV5** is the most widely used serotype in NHPs
(36% of experiments, per Tremblay et al., 2020) - **AAV9** is second
most common (13%), followed by AAV2 variants - **AAV-DJ** shows broad
tropism and is increasingly popular for enhanced transduction -
**AAV2-retro** provides efficient retrograde access for pathway-specific
manipulation

